recordings.file-name: XC554204-chevalier gambette, cris vol nuit, Bondues, 3 mai 2020.mp3

recordings.rmk: Slight snowfall landing on mic.

Recorded:

  • call, tyuuuu, at 0:02, 0:05.4 and 0:42.5
  • (alarm) call, tyuk-tyuk-tyuk-tyuk-... or kyip-kyip-kyip-kyip-..., at 0:12.6 and 0:33.5
  • call, teu-huhu, at 0:49.7 and 0:52.4

General observations: Wet pastures close to a shallow sea bay. A Common Redshank is calling from the ground

Recording remarks: NatureGuides (2020) describes the tyuuuu call as an alert call. In this recording it is centered around 2,3 kHz and are around 0.5 seconds long. The calls are longer and lower-pitched compared with somewhat similar calls in XC548964, which according to NatureGuides (2020) assessment could be considered to be a mate-call. The tyuk-tyuk-tyuk-tyuk-... call is described by NatureGuides (2020) as an alarm call. Svensson et al (2009) renders the alarm call of the Redshank as kyip-kyip-kyip-kyip-....

Other distinguishable species:

  • Common Goldeneye, Bucephala clangula, wing-beats, at e.g. 0:00.9 (vaguely)
  • Great Spotted Woodpecker Dendrocopos major, drumming, at 0:08.2 (vaguely)
  • Eurasian Skylark, Alauda arvensis, call, prreeh-e, at 0:16.5
  • Northern Lapwing, Vanellus vanellus, song, at 0:18.6 (vaguely)
  • Mew Gull, Larus canus, long-call, kiä, at 0:28.8 (vaguely); "laughing" call, at 0:31.3 (vaguely)
  • Common Chaffinch, Fringilla coelebs, song, at 0:44 (vaguely)
  • Unidentified, call, at 0:47.4

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore; Svensson, Mullarney and Zetterström, 2009, Collins Bird Guide, Second Edition, HarperCollinsPublishers

recordings.type: alarm call, i think this is an alarm call
recordings.rmk:
Recorded with my ZOOM H5 Handy Recorder

Common Redshank standing on a rock giving what I think is an alarm calls. I approached and the bird continued with the alarm call but the bird didn´t move. 


So I sneaked closer and closer to the bird that continued to give alarm calls. I looked around so it didn´t looked like there was a nest close by. 


And in the North of Finland they have babies so I guess the nesting sesson should be over here down south.


But maybe they are having their second brood, but no sign of any nest and I moved closer.

[Picture 1](http://www.aladdin.st/bird-watching/germany/55.jpg)
